Title : Yiddisher Arbeter Sport Klub (Antwerp)
Text : '''''Yiddisher Arbeter Sport Klub''''' (Yiddish for 'Jewish Workers Sports Club', abbreviated '''YASK'''; {{lang-nl|Joodse Arbeiders Sportklub}}, abbreviated '''JASK''') was a Jewish sports organization in [[Antwerp]], [[Belgium]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Bijdragen tot de eigentijdse geschiedenis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1U1sAAAAIAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Centre d'études guerres et sociétés contemporaines|page=340}}</ref> It was founded in 1936.<ref name="a">Lapiower, Alain. ''[http://www.cegesoma.be/docs/media/chtp_beg/chtp_08/chtp8_011_lapiower.pdf Fin de siècle pour des jeunes juifs progressistes - L’Union sportive des Jeunes Juifs – Union des Jeunes Juifs progressistes, 1944-1978]''</ref> YASK was linked to the [[Communist Party of Belgium]].<ref name="Doorslaer1997">{{cite book|author=Rudi van Doorslaer|title=Enfants du ghetto: Juifs révolutionnaires en Belgique (1925-1940)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=61pKAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Labor|isbn=978-2-8040-1139-0|page=48}}</ref><ref name="WEINSTOCK2013"/> A product of the [[Popular Front]] era, YASK was set up as an open sports organization for the Jewish population at large. The club emphasized [[anti-fascism]], whilst maintaining a neutral stand on [[Zionism]].<ref name="Mikhman1998">{{cite book|author=Dan Mikhman|title=Belgium and the Holocaust: Jews, Belgians, Germans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gpk7P_mMFyUC&pg=PA74|year=1998|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-965-308-068-3|page=74}}</ref>

YASK sent a troupe to the 1937 People's Olympics in [[Barcelona]].<ref name="WEINSTOCK2013">{{cite book|author=Nathan WEINSTOCK|title=Le pain de misère: Histoire du mouvement ouvrier juif en Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5edCyn9WaesC&pg=PR271|date=23 May 2013|publisher=LA DECOUVERTE|isbn=978-2-7071-7230-3|page=cclxxi}}</ref> YASK members were active in the United Jewish Help Committee for Spain in Antwerp.<ref>{{cite book|title=BTNG|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=adEKAQAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=SOMA-CEGES|page=172}}</ref>

YASK served as a pool for recruitment for resistance cells during the [[Second World War]].<ref name="a"/>

